<paragraph id="8BC93698FFB374465B96FA10244A3DB0" blockId="28.[142,758,1468,1674]" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">
<emphasis id="B902EA8AFFB374465B96FA1027233EE8" box="[142,261,1469,1490]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Sponges in alpha and beta forms. Delicate tylostyles as megascleres accompanied by microspined (rarely smooth) microxea and microspined microrhabds as microscleres. Microrhabds are usually straight or bent but may also be centrotylote and sinuose. Microxeas do not have a particular location or orientation in the tissue (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE74B69FFB374465AADF9D924463DB0" author="Rutzler K" box="[437,608,1652,1674]" pageId="28" pageNumber="381" pagination="1" refId="ref25389" refString="Rutzler K. 2002 a. Family Clionaidae D'Orbigny, 1951. In: Hooper NA, Soest RWM Van, eds. Systema Porifera: a guide to the classification of sponges 1. New York: Kluwer Academic." type="book chapter" year="2002">Rützler, 2002a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
