<paragraph id="8BC93698FFB37446583EFBD625BB3E9F" blockId="28.[806,1422,1147,1445]" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">
<emphasis id="B902EA8AFFB37446583EFBD625883FAA" box="[806,942,1147,1168]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Description:</emphasis>
Boring sponge always growing in alpha stage. The species reaches a maximum surface of 
<quantity id="4C8E9B7DFFB374465E45FB3425563FF7" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.4" metricValueMax="5.5" metricValueMin="3.3" pageId="28" pageNumber="381" unit="cm" value="4.4" valueMax="5.5" valueMin="3.3">3.3– 5.5 cm</quantity>
<superScript id="7C039BD0FFB374465868FB19255E3FF8" attach="left" box="[880,888,1204,1218]" fontSize="6" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">2</superScript>
. The inhalant papillae are circular, and very small in diameter (from 83 to 800 Mm), making them very difficult to see 
<emphasis id="B902EA8AFFB374465F1CFB5B226B3E31" box="[1028,1101,1270,1291]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">in situ</emphasis>
. They are 
<quantity id="4C8E9B7DFFB374465FDBFB58236F3E31" box="[1219,1353,1269,1291]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.25" metricValueMax="2.4" metricValueMin="0.1" pageId="28" pageNumber="381" unit="mm" value="1.25" valueMax="2.4" valueMin="0.1">0.1–2.4 mm</quantity>
apart and evenly scattered on the entire surface. Oscules are circular, very small in size, from 33.2 to 132.8 Mm in diameter. Papillae are never fused, and do not protrude. Sponge is very light orange in life, pale yellow in alcohol.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC93698FFB37446583EFA10222E3C3F" blockId="28.[806,1422,1469,1797]" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">
<emphasis id="B902EA8AFFB37446583EFA1022203EE8" box="[806,1030,1469,1490]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Skeletal characters:</emphasis>
There are 
<specimenCount id="9D70FD11FFB374465F91FA10232F3EE8" box="[1161,1289,1469,1491]" pageId="28" pageNumber="381" type="generic" typeStatus="types">three types</specimenCount>
of spicules. (i) Straight tylostyles, with well-formed globular heads, sometimes with a small terminal knob, and gradually tapering to the end (
<figureCitation id="134D2A1DFFB374465F81F9B422DA3D15" box="[1177,1276,1561,1583]" captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="29.[155,233,1550,1569]" captionTargetBox="[169,1420,197,1518]" captionTargetId="figure-146@29.[169,1420,197,1518]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 19. Pione carpenteri: A, head and tip of a tylostyle; B, oxeas with minute spines; C, straight microrhabds; D, detail of the ornamentation of the oxea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5430972" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5430972/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Fig. 19A</figureCitation>
). They measure 171 ¥ 4 Mm on average (9.5 Mm head width) (
<tableCitation id="C6F40323FFB374465835F9FB25A53D56" box="[813,899,1622,1644]" captionStart="Table 9" captionStartId="30.[142,206,197,216]" captionText="Table 9. Comparative data for the dimensions of the spicules (in Mm) of Pione carpenteri specimens. Values in parentheses are means" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Table 9</tableCitation>
). (ii) Stout fusiform oxeas, finely microspined, straight or bent in the centre, where a nodule sometimes appears (on average 84 ¥ 4 Mm) (
<figureCitation id="134D2A1DFFB374465FE3F93E23A43D93" box="[1275,1410,1683,1705]" captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="29.[155,233,1550,1569]" captionTargetBox="[169,1420,197,1518]" captionTargetId="figure-146@29.[169,1420,197,1518]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 19. Pione carpenteri: A, head and tip of a tylostyle; B, oxeas with minute spines; C, straight microrhabds; D, detail of the ornamentation of the oxea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5430972" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5430972/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Fig. 19B, D</figureCitation>
). (iii) Straight microspined microrhabds, slightly fusiform, and characteristically with obtuse ends (average 12.6 Mm) (
<figureCitation id="134D2A1DFFB374465882F94225DA3C3F" box="[922,1020,1775,1797]" captionStart="Figure 19" captionStartId="29.[155,233,1550,1569]" captionTargetBox="[169,1420,197,1518]" captionTargetId="figure-146@29.[169,1420,197,1518]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="Figure 19. Pione carpenteri: A, head and tip of a tylostyle; B, oxeas with minute spines; C, straight microrhabds; D, detail of the ornamentation of the oxea." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5430972" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5430972/files/figure.png" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Fig. 19C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC93698FFB37446583EF8B0254B3C4B" blockId="28.[806,1422,1821,1905]" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">
<emphasis id="B902EA8AFFB37446583EF8B025913C08" box="[806,951,1821,1842]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Distribution:</emphasis>
Mazatlán (
<collectingRegion id="49B2F87AFFB374465F58F8B022BF3C09" box="[1088,1177,1821,1843]" country="Mexico" name="Sinaloa" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">Sinaloa</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F3617608FFB374465FB0F8B022DC3C09" box="[1192,1274,1821,1843]" name="Mexico" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">México</collectingCountry>
, east Pacific Ocean) (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE74B69FFB37446589CF891220B3C68" author="Hancock A" box="[900,1069,1852,1874]" pageId="28" pageNumber="381" pagination="229 - 242" refId="ref24703" refString="Hancock A. 1867. Note on the excavating sponges; with description of four new species. Annals and Magazine of Natural History 19 (3): 229 - 242." type="journal article" year="1867">Hancock, 1867</bibRefCitation>
), Indian Ocean (
<bibRefCitation id="EFE74B69FFB374465FF0F89125473C4B" author="Calcinai B &amp; Cerrano C &amp; Sara M &amp; Bavestrello G" pageId="28" pageNumber="381" pagination="203 - 219" refId="ref23901" refString="Calcinai B, Cerrano C, Sara M, Bavestrello G. 2000. Boring sponges (Porifera, Demospongiae) from the Indian Ocean. Italian Journal of Zoology 67: 203 - 219." type="journal article" year="2000">
Calcinai 
<emphasis id="B902EA8AFFB374465E57F89023A63C6B" box="[1359,1408,1852,1874]" italics="true" pageId="28" pageNumber="381">et al</emphasis>
., 2000
</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF096610FFB274475B83F9A327DA3D05" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5430972" ID-Zenodo-Dep="5430972" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5430972/files/figure.png" pageId="29" pageNumber="382" startId="29.[155,233,1550,1569]" targetBox="[169,1420,197,1518]" targetPageId="29">
